4 SYNOPSIS:
5 This bill would establish a formal process
6 requiring the Legislative Services Agency to complete a
7 Rural Impact Report if so requested by a legislator on
8 any bill pending before the Legislature.
9 This bill would specify the issues that must be
10 assessed in a Rural Impact Report, including the impact
11 on school systems and consequences to farmers and
12 agricultural businesses, broken down by legislative
13 districts and affected rural communities, and would
14 require the incorporation of data from experts and
15 rural stakeholders.
16 This bill would establish a time frame for
17 completing a report.
18
19
20 A BILL
21 TO BE ENTITLED
22 AN ACT
23
24 Relating to the Legislature; to require the Legislative
25 Services Agency to complete a Rural Impact Report on a bill,
26 if so requested; and to set parameters for the contents of a
27 report.
28 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
Page 1

BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
HB558 INTRODUCED
29 Section 1. This act shall be known as the Reviewing
30 Urban-Rural Asymmetries in Legislation (RURAL) Act.
31 Section 2. The purpose of this act is to ensure that
32 proposed legislation is evaluated for its potential effects on
33 rural communities, agricultural stakeholders, and rural school
34 districts before enactment, promoting informed decision-making
35 and transparency in the legislative process. Additionally,
36 this act provides comparative analysis between rural,
37 suburban, and urban districts to highlight disparities and
38 ensure balanced policymaking.
39 Section 3. (a) Any member of the Legislature may submit
40 a formal request for a Rural Impact Report on any bill
41 introduced in a legislative session.
42 (b) Requests shall be submitted to the Legislative
43 Services Agency, which shall be responsible for conducting the
44 assessment.
45 Section 4. (a) A Rural Impact Report shall include all
46 of the following:
47 (1) An analysis of the bill's direct and indirect
48 effects on rural communities, including economic, social, and
49 regulatory impacts.
50 (2) A specific assessment of the potential consequences
51 for farmers and agricultural businesses.
52 (3) A localized breakdown of effects by legislative
53 district and affected rural communities.
54 (4) A comparative analysis of the bill's projected
55 impact on rural districts versus suburban and urban districts,
56 including any identified disparities or differential
Page 2

including any identified disparities or differential
HB558 INTRODUCED
57 consequences.
58 (5) An assessment of the bill's impact on rural school
59 districts, including, but not limited to, school funding and
60 budget allocations; student enrollment and demographic shifts;
61 access to educational resources, including technology and
62 extracurricular programs; teacher recruitment, retention, and
63 workforce stability; and potential for school closures or
64 consolidations due to legislative changes.
65 (6) Identification of potential benefits, costs, and
66 unintended consequences of the proposed legislation.
67 (b) Reports shall incorporate data from relevant
68 agencies, industry experts, education officials, and rural
69 stakeholders to ensure accuracy and comprehensiveness.
70 Section 5. (a) The Legislative Services Agency shall
71 endeavor to complete the Rural Impact Report within 30 days of
72 receiving a valid request.
73 (b) If additional time is needed due to data
74 limitations, the Legislative Services Agency shall notify the
75 requesting legislator in writing with an estimated completion
76 date.
77 Section 6. (a) Completed Rural Impact Reports shall be
78 made publicly available through the official website of the
79 Legislature.
80 (b) Copies shall also be provided to the requesting
81 legislator, relevant legislative committees, and rural
82 stakeholder organizations upon request.
83 Section 7. This act shall become effective on October
84 1, 2026.
